    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.9.0-dev-490+gf96fb23de6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\n-\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux rolling\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.12.0-dev (6566dd3d)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nArch User Repository (AUR)\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\nnvim --clean\r\n:lua local i = io.popen('>&2 echo \"error\"'); local o = i:read('*all'); i:close(); print('out: ', o);\r\n:lua vim.keymap.set('n', 'x', function() local i = io.popen('>&2 echo \"error\"'); local o = i:read('*all'); i:close(); print('out: ', o); end)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nText that is sent to `stderr` should be displayed as an error under `:messages`.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\n### Initial state with open `:h user-manual`\r\n\r\n![Initial state](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16037346/206880544-dc4b7817-86e9-434a-991e-c95f330a627f.png)\r\n\r\n### After executing `:lua local i = io.popen('>&2 echo \"error\"'); local o = i:read('*all'); i:close(); print('out: ', o);`\r\n\r\nAfter the execution the text that got sent to `stderr` is shown at the beginning of the command-line, seemingly overwriting previously written text, it also shifts the statusbar at the same time breaking the layout.\r\n![After lua execution in commandl-line](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16037346/206880548-8d9dba10-a8bd-4c71-9054-0f2518b79dd9.png)\r\n\r\n### After mapping it to a key `:lua vim.keymap.set('n', 'x', function() local i = io.popen('>&2 echo \"error\"'); local o = i:read('*all'); i:close(); print('out: ', o); end)`\r\n\r\nBinding the Lua expressions to key, here `x` in normal mode, lets us see that the message from `stderr` is directly printed at the cursor location, it is not editing/changing the contents of the buffer.\r\n\r\n![After key-mapping](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16037346/206880546-a2ca22a5-8f68-4757-b0c8-505eb7f864da.png)\r\n",
